      {
        "identifier": "D",
        "content": "I > II > III"
      }
    ],
    "correct_options": [
      "A"
    ],
    "answer": null,
    "explanation": "<p>Stability of the given cations can be\nunderstood by the following structures</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/jaoe38c1m3o8ieqf/41899ecc-9836-4df2-802c-edb523338b94/264cf270-a656-11ef-a4a0-dbe08b0b7be0/file-jaoe38c1m3o8ieqg.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/jaoe38c1m3o8ieqf/41899ecc-9836-4df2-802c-edb523338b94/264cf270-a656-11ef-a4a0-dbe08b0b7be0/file-jaoe38c1m3o8ieqg.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\" alt=\"AIIMS 2018 Chemistry - Some Basic Concepts of Organic Chemistry Question 2 English Explanation\"></p>\n<p>Thus, the stability of carbocation decreases in the order,</p>\n<p>II &gt; I &gt; III</p>",
